  "doc_id": "12704",
  "text": "As a basis for comparison, the single-factor model was used to test whether the most general construct of behavioral and emotional strengths was consistent with the item response variances. A bifactor version of the correlated-factor model was fit to provide an additional perspective on the internal structure of the assessment by partitioning item response variance into common sources [CITATION_1] . The bifactor model assumes that each item response has two sources of variance: the general factor and one of the four group factors (Emotional Regulation, School Readiness, etc.). Thus, the bifactor model can complement a correlated factors model \"by evaluating whether item response variance is due to a general construct versus group factors\" (Brouwer, Meijer, & Zevalkink, 2013, p. 138) .",
